<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="110" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1388,1520]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1388,1413]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Tubercula pubertatis extend for 
<number box="[658,699,1389,1413]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5</number>
segments in the region of segments 
<number box="[1135,1208,1389,1413]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="21.0" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="19.0">19–23</number>
. Posterior setae are arranged in regular series, or some regular and others irregular, or in quincunx. Some anterior septa present unconventional parietal insertion (
<bibRefCitation author="Righi" box="[543,677,1461,1485]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" refString="Righi, G. (1984) Pontoscolex (Oligochaeta, Glossoscolecidae) a new evaluation. Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment, 19, 159 - 177." type="journal article" year="1984">
Righi 
<number box="[617,677,1461,1485]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Number of species: 
<number box="[932,963,1461,1485]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="16.0">16</number>
. Distribution: 
<collectingCountry box="[1131,1198,1461,1485]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="110">Brasil</collectingCountry>
(
<number box="[1217,1248,1461,1485]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="10.0">10</number>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[1271,1386,1461,1485]" name="Venezuela" pageId="7" pageNumber="110">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(
<number box="[1405,1421,1461,1485]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="2.0">2</number>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[151,284,1496,1520]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="7" pageNumber="110">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
(
<number box="[300,316,1496,1520]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="2.0">2</number>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[337,447,1496,1520]" name="Colombia" pageId="7" pageNumber="110">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<number box="[465,477,1496,1520]" pageId="7" pageNumber="110" value="1.0">1</number>
) and one species pantropical.
</paragraph>
